00:12:33.970 --> 00:12:37.360
everyone kind of has to do when they wanna
go on a fun trip but isn't, in and of itself,

00:12:37.360 --> 00:12:41.380
all the exciting or enjoyable of an experience
and really kind of improve it.

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:44.620
And, especially, make it more mobile friendly.

00:12:44.620 --> 00:12:48.150
It tends to be a little information overload
and, so, what we've really tried to do is

00:12:48.150 --> 00:12:52.790
get a lot of information across in a very
visual way and the biggest thing that that's

00:12:52.790 --> 00:12:55.620
led for us is a lot of fans of the app.

00:12:55.620 --> 00:12:58.130
We've taken the Android design guidelines
very seriously.

00:12:58.130 --> 00:13:02.660
We haven't done it perfectly but I think everybody's
trying to find exactly how their brand and

00:13:02.660 --> 00:13:07.440
Android can really work together and, you
know, a little bit of harsh feedback is all

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:11.600
it takes to get you to really look at something
in a new way and that flexibility ends up

00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:12.600
with a much better app.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:15.220
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: So, I wish we could show you
the app on screen.

00:13:15.220 --> 00:13:22.370
Today we had some issues with our MHL connector
which I'm sure many of you can sympathize

00:13:22.370 --> 00:13:23.370
with.

00:13:23.370 --> 00:13:24.370
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: But I've got the app in front

00:13:24.370 --> 00:13:25.370
of me.

00:13:25.370 --> 00:13:26.370
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Sure.

00:13:26.370 --> 00:13:28.170
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: and, Ryan, why don't you tell
us a little bit about, you know, what you

00:13:28.170 --> 00:13:29.310
could change if you could.

00:13:29.310 --> 00:13:33.190
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Okay, well, the first thing I definitely
agree with is that the home screen is kind

00:13:33.190 --> 00:13:36.210
of a dashboard, kind of a list and Android's
kind of moved away from that.

00:13:36.210 --> 00:13:41.780
The only thing that I'm afraid of if I give
this up is the, like, unavoidable knowledge

00:13:41.780 --> 00:13:44.920
a user has the moment they launch this app
of what this app can do.

00:13:44.920 --> 00:13:50.170
If you use a little picker on the left, which
I actually did do on tablets where this really

00:13:50.170 --> 00:13:54.380
was very awkward, I did, unfortunately, get
a couple of emails of people asking how to

00:13:54.380 --> 00:13:57.930
get from hotel search to flight search, which
I launched them into hotels at first.

00:13:57.930 --> 00:13:58.930
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Right.

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:00.970
&gt;&gt;Ryan: So that's kind of made me a little
timid about it.

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:05.810
What approach I'm thinking of taking is instead
of kind of getting rid of a screen like this,

00:14:05.810 --> 00:14:07.440
make it more useful of a screen.

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:11.440
So instead of hiding the recent searches off
in flights or off in hotels, maybe I could

00:14:11.440 --> 00:14:14.570
put them right here in front so you could
pop right back where you were last time you

00:14:14.570 --> 00:14:15.570
launched the app.

00:14:15.570 --> 00:14:16.570
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Absolutely.

00:14:16.570 --> 00:14:20.700
This is really tough and I think we've, we've
had to deal with this a lot as we've switched

00:14:20.700 --> 00:14:26.300
from the old Gingerbread design guidelines
into the Ice Cream Sandwich world is a lot

00:14:26.300 --> 00:14:30.920
of these things are not discoverable on their
own but they become obvious over time.

00:14:30.920 --> 00:14:36.310
You know, the same way that it used to be
that any hyperlink on a website was, you know,

00:14:36.310 --> 00:14:42.041
underlined and in blue but it had a really
sharp "click me" attitude to it and now a

00:14:42.041 --> 00:14:45.970
lot of times you won't even see hyperlinks
differentiated until you hover over them because

00:14:45.970 --> 00:14:47.800
people know how they work.

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:52.340
So we're hoping to get to the point that people
just know how left side navigation work and

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:56.920
that's one of the reasons we harp on it but
you're absolutely right that adding more discoverability,

00:14:56.920 --> 00:15:00.920
especially for new users, is a great idea.

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:06.780
I wanna go really quickly to Roman to see
if he's got any ideas of how you can make

00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:13.180
things discoverable without always presenting
the user with a dashboard as soon as they

00:15:13.180 --> 00:15:14.180
log in.

00:15:14.180 --> 00:15:15.180
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Sure.

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:19.426
&gt;&gt;Roman Nurik: Yeah, so, I think the point
about, first of all just to talk a little

00:15:19.426 --> 00:15:23.930
bit about the dashboard, I think the point
that, Ryan, you're making about having like

00:15:23.930 --> 00:15:27.930
a more content rich dashboard, that's a good
start.

00:15:27.930 --> 00:15:33.910
I mean, that becomes less of a dashboard and
really more of a dashboard or true dashboard.

00:15:33.910 --> 00:15:41.430
I know that sounds weird but basically I think
that's kind of playing into what, actually

00:15:41.430 --> 00:15:46.164
I think one of the mock ups we did for Kayak
was like, instead of having, you know, instead

00:15:46.164 --> 00:15:53.050
of having a decision between hotels and flights,
actually show the users all this information

00:15:53.050 --> 00:15:56.240
in one place centered around the concept of
a trip.

00:15:56.240 --> 00:16:00.330
And that point, I mean, they don't have to
think about, you know, is there hotel functionality

00:16:00.330 --> 00:16:04.620
search, you know, flight functionality, you
know, they just think in the concept of, "Oh,

00:16:04.620 --> 00:16:07.960
I have a trip and here are the different things
I can do on my trip."

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:14.430
But to talk a little bit about the discoverability,
this is something that users of newer devices

00:16:14.430 --> 00:16:16.120
are being trained on.

00:16:16.120 --> 00:16:21.290
So as soon as they launch maps, as soon as
they launch Gmail, they're learning, they're

00:16:21.290 --> 00:16:24.290
starting to understand what spinner navigation
is.

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:30.990
So, while there are some users that may just
not ever touch that, we're doing a better

00:16:30.990 --> 00:16:32.279
job of training them.

00:16:32.279 --> 00:16:36.630
So, like Ian said, it's really great, over
time this will be less and less of a problem.

00:16:36.630 --> 00:16:42.760
But, I mean, in terms of other things, you
could have kind of a pop up, you know, kind

00:16:42.760 --> 00:16:47.200
of blue circles indicating, "Hey, there's
more stuff here" we don't recommend generally

00:16:47.200 --> 00:16:50.920
doing that because things like the action
bar spinner should be discoverable on their

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:55.630
own but if you absolutely must direct attention
to something, you could do something like

00:16:55.630 --> 00:16:56.630
that.

00:16:56.630 --> 00:16:59.940
And I think we mentioned this last time but
there's an open source project called Showcase

00:16:59.940 --> 00:17:04.190
view that can kind of give you that rich,
you know, zoom in to a specific UI element.

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:08.799
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: One thing we used to do in
video games that I think would be really difficult

00:17:08.799 --> 00:17:15.049
to do, like would be incredibly difficult
machine learning exercise but with a video

00:17:15.049 --> 00:17:18.539
game it was a lot easier, you could detect
when the user was frustrated and when they

00:17:18.539 --> 00:17:20.802
couldn't figure out how to pass the level
and give them hints.

00:17:20.802 --> 00:17:26.990
You know, I'd love it if you could say, "Oh,"
well okay, now I'm getting into clippy territory

00:17:26.990 --> 00:17:27.990
but-
[Laughter]

00:17:27.990 --> 00:17:31.500
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: "Obviously you're trying to
find hotel, it's up here!"

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:37.910
Yeah, I like the task oriented view with the
idea that the navigation is something that

00:17:37.910 --> 00:17:43.470
would jump you ahead or behind with the task
without having to be the only way.

00:17:43.470 --> 00:17:47.999
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Yeah, to say something in less words
than the spinner, I am looking forward to

00:17:47.999 --> 00:17:50.299
the day that that is just the way UI works
on Android.

00:17:50.299 --> 00:17:52.090
I feel like that's a great way to do it.

00:17:52.090 --> 00:17:56.720
Dashboards, they were kind of a solution to
a problem that's now been solved better and

00:17:56.720 --> 00:17:59.429
we're just kind of waiting for the mainstream
to catch up a little bit.

00:17:59.429 --> 00:18:03.499
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: Yeah, I think, it's been mentioned
a couple of times already but I think the

00:18:03.499 --> 00:18:08.210
solution which Roman's describing actually
fits in really well with one of your key points

00:18:08.210 --> 00:18:11.460
which was the ability to plan your entire
trip so you're kind of getting away from that,

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:15.600
"I wanna plan a flight, I wanna book a hotel"
and you're just saying, "I wanna organize

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:18.830
a trip" and there's a logical work flow that
goes there.

00:18:18.830 --> 00:18:22.639
So if you haven't done one of those elements
you're kind of prompted that, "Hey, you booked

00:18:22.639 --> 00:18:25.039
a hotel but how you gonna get there?"

00:18:25.039 --> 00:18:28.549
So, being able to sort of flow it that way
could be quite interesting particularly if

00:18:28.549 --> 00:18:31.830
you can have it enter, you should have a vector
that people wanna start with.

00:18:31.830 --> 00:18:35.619
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Yeah and then the sort of navigation
that doesn't feel like you go into something

00:18:35.619 --> 00:18:36.840
and come all the way back out.

00:18:36.840 --> 00:18:38.000
It's kind of a circle.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:39.000
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: Exactly.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:40.649
&gt;&gt;Ryan: I think that could work really well.

00:18:40.649 --> 00:18:41.850
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Cool.

00:18:41.850 --> 00:18:43.450
Now, let's talk a little bit about this.

00:18:43.450 --> 00:18:44.450
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Yeah.

00:18:44.450 --> 00:18:45.450
My favorite part of the feedback.

00:18:45.450 --> 00:18:49.429
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Ryan: So, our location selector when you're

00:18:49.429 --> 00:18:52.740
trying to say where you're flying from or
where you're flying to has a pretty critical

00:18:52.740 --> 00:18:57.309
flaw in the current live version which is
that if the place you're trying to go isn't

00:18:57.309 --> 00:19:04.990
in our auto correct library and you hit the
done button on the keyboard, it actually nukes

00:19:04.990 --> 00:19:06.919
whatever you've typed out of existence.

00:19:06.919 --> 00:19:08.899
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Ryan: And this is just, you know, it's a

00:19:08.899 --> 00:19:14.139
perfect example of something I don't personally
do so I just never knew existed until I stared

00:19:14.139 --> 00:19:15.919
it right in the face in App Clinic.

00:19:15.919 --> 00:19:17.790
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Ryan: So that was like the best feedback

00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:20.840
I got because I'm sure there's more than one
person out there annoyed by that.

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:21.840
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Right.

00:19:21.840 --> 00:19:25.499
This is where, for those of you who can't
see the phone, this is where I type in V-E-N-I,

00:19:25.499 --> 00:19:31.570
thinking about Venice, it gives me the choice
of either Venice, Florida or the Athens International

00:19:31.570 --> 00:19:33.870
Airport and, yes,

00:19:33.870 --> 00:19:42.110
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: I’m gonna try to be clever,
warning.

00:19:42.110 --> 00:19:43.110
[Laughter]

00:19:43.110 --> 00:19:52.279
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: So it'll either give me Venice,
Florida or the Athens International Airport

00:19:52.279 --> 00:19:56.159
and I think to myself, "Oh, neither one of
those is correct" so I hit done on the keyboard

00:19:56.159 --> 00:19:59.179
cause I just wanna keep typing and then it
nukes what I've typed in.

00:19:59.179 --> 00:20:01.240
&gt;&gt;Ryan: So this is actually an interesting
thing.

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:02.730
I've since fixed that.

00:20:02.730 --> 00:20:05.669
I haven't released the update because there's
a few other things I wanna do to and I like

00:20:05.669 --> 00:20:06.669
to be not too annoying with my updates.

00:20:06.669 --> 00:20:14.070
But, the reason I do it is I found that when
I typed into one of these auto completes,

00:20:14.070 --> 00:20:17.821
I would type in "San Fran" and I'd say San
Francisco and I'd be like, "Oh, actually I

00:20:17.821 --> 00:20:21.919
didn't want that one I wanted South San Francisco"
arbitrary example, so, on the next click I

00:20:21.919 --> 00:20:26.989
nuke whatever was in there and then what you
would type would just pop up in a little hinter.

00:20:26.989 --> 00:20:30.399
The nice thing about that is you never have
to backspace like 30 characters you didn't

00:20:30.399 --> 00:20:32.070
want which is kind of, extremely annoying.

00:20:32.070 --> 00:20:33.070
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Right.

00:20:33.070 --> 00:20:36.590
&gt;&gt;Ryan: The downside of that is I didn't have
the case handled for that done on the keyboard

00:20:36.590 --> 00:20:41.409
so I was thinking you clicked on it again,
you gave it focus again by clicking on it

00:20:41.409 --> 00:20:42.970
so whatever you typed is gone.

00:20:42.970 --> 00:20:43.970
I've since fixed that.

00:20:43.970 --> 00:20:47.330
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: You know, I have to say I
think that you got a really good point there

00:20:47.330 --> 00:20:51.880
but I feel like there's more to it than that
because a lot of times, cause I've seen things

00:20:51.880 --> 00:20:58.179
that do behave the way that you're describing,
in fact, Chrome does this sometimes and it

00:20:58.179 --> 00:21:02.841
really just kills me, I feel like I'm typing
a certain and what I really want is something

00:21:02.841 --> 00:21:08.881
very similar to one that I've already searched
but not quite exactly the same so I want it

00:21:08.881 --> 00:21:12.090
to auto complete and then I want to be able
to change it slightly.

00:21:12.090 --> 00:21:14.409
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Chrome does that to me too.

00:21:14.409 --> 00:21:18.320
Like, if I search two words and then I go
back and wanna search just the first, I'll

00:21:18.320 --> 00:21:21.760
type the first and hit enter, it'll assume
I meant the whole two words and you're like,

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:22.760
"No!

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:24.090
That's not what I meant at all!"

00:21:24.090 --> 00:21:25.090
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Exactly.

00:21:25.090 --> 00:21:29.519
But I think we all loved your flight search
results page.

00:21:29.519 --> 00:21:32.739
&gt;&gt;Ryan: That's my favorite part of the app
and I think that's pretty true for everyone.

00:21:32.739 --> 00:21:37.200
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: And especially the way it
integrates with our calendar and the agony

00:21:37.200 --> 00:21:38.200
thing, that's awesome.

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:39.309
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Although, I think I mentioned

00:21:39.309 --> 00:21:41.149
I really wanted more to it.

00:21:41.149 --> 00:21:42.190
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Yeah.

00:21:42.190 --> 00:21:48.419
So the balance we're trying to strike there
is, the best mobile apps tend to do like a

00:21:48.419 --> 00:21:53.690
core set of things and it's easy to like,
keep adding features as you finished some

00:21:53.690 --> 00:21:58.679
and you kind of have the dev time, or something
like that and, like, frequent flyer miles,

00:21:58.679 --> 00:22:03.149
you know, selecting preferred airlines and
all that stuff could be really cool to tuck

00:22:03.149 --> 00:22:08.549
in there somewhere but I don't know if I'm
entirely convinced that just keeping it very

00:22:08.549 --> 00:22:10.480
simple is the worst idea.

00:22:10.480 --> 00:22:14.650
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: I think you're absolutely
right but I would counter with, sort of, what's

00:22:14.650 --> 00:22:17.960
worked for us at Google which is you wanna
keep the interface very, very simple.

00:22:17.960 --> 00:22:23.400
I don't want anything to change in what I
just did but I wanna have that magical feeling

00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:28.799
of realizing, "Oh, hey, the results you gave
me fit my life perfectly because I don't just

00:22:28.799 --> 00:22:29.950
have a calendar.

00:22:29.950 --> 00:22:35.090
I also tend to fly this airline or I want
a window seat or I've got this many frequent

00:22:35.090 --> 00:22:36.090
flyer miles."

00:22:36.090 --> 00:22:37.090
&gt;&gt;Ryan: You make a good point.

00:22:37.090 --> 00:22:42.460
The distinction between UI, like screen space
being taken up by something, an actual functionality,

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:47.119
it is actually not unreasonable to think we
could add that in, sort of, a setting screen

00:22:47.119 --> 00:22:49.830
where you don't even have to know it exists,
it doesn't clutter anything to do with what's

00:22:49.830 --> 00:22:53.389
already been done but you can get the benefit
of it if you want it.

00:22:53.389 --> 00:22:54.389
That's pretty reasonable.

00:22:54.389 --> 00:22:55.389
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Absolutely.

00:22:55.389 --> 00:22:58.890
There are a few things, you know, for instance,
the agony of a particular flight goes down

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:05.971
if this long layover happens to be in a place
with a really good frequent flyer club, for

00:23:05.971 --> 00:23:06.971
instance.

00:23:06.971 --> 00:23:07.971
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Yeah, definitely.

00:23:07.971 --> 00:23:10.139
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: But what are the color codings
mean?

00:23:10.139 --> 00:23:14.179
&gt;&gt;Ryan: So, colors are specifically chosen
to be, like you guys hit on it when you were

00:23:14.179 --> 00:23:15.860
talking in the App Clinic, it's to do with
airlines.

00:23:15.860 --> 00:23:20.470
So, Delta's blue, United, or Delta's orange,
United is blue and NA is like a light green.

00:23:20.470 --> 00:23:24.549
We tried to do it as true to the colors they
picked for their brand as possible.

00:23:24.549 --> 00:23:29.600
In truth, we could have done arbitrary colors
but since it was already gonna be kind of

00:23:29.600 --> 00:23:33.289
a rainbow we tried to give as much meaning
to it as possible.

00:23:33.289 --> 00:23:36.601
For most people who don't really care about
the names of the airline or the color of the

00:23:36.601 --> 00:23:39.539
airline it's just nicer looking than a whole
bunch of the same color.

00:23:39.539 --> 00:23:41.120
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: That's a really good point.

00:23:41.120 --> 00:23:45.950
I would love to see a feature where they're
separated by alliance because there's only

00:23:45.950 --> 00:23:48.429
like four alliances that make any difference
at all.

00:23:48.429 --> 00:23:51.250
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Yeah, well that's the, the biggest
thing is often people think that they want

00:23:51.250 --> 00:23:53.529
a preferred airline but really they want a
preferred alliance.

00:23:53.529 --> 00:23:54.529
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Absolutely.

00:23:54.529 --> 00:23:56.899
&gt;&gt;Ryan: So, stuff like that can really make
a difference.

00:23:56.899 --> 00:24:00.000
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Yeah, I can see how you could
really change things around.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:05.029
Well, I think we're almost out of time but
let's just really quick talk about the hotel

00:24:05.029 --> 00:24:08.299
search which we thought was very similar in
a lot of ways to flight search.

00:24:08.299 --> 00:24:12.940
It felt like some things were missing, like
there weren't as many, I don't think you have

00:24:12.940 --> 00:24:14.580
the previous searches listed.

00:24:14.580 --> 00:24:15.580
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Yes.

00:24:15.580 --> 00:24:20.710
So I do have them in the background but the
big design goal when they originally designed

00:24:20.710 --> 00:24:25.380
hotels or what I call intels which is our
hotel search product, which is that you were

00:24:25.380 --> 00:24:29.059
always looking at the map, you never lost
this anchor, which you guys even picked up

00:24:29.059 --> 00:24:33.330
on in the App Clinic cause you couldn't really
get away from the map until you picked a hotel.

00:24:33.330 --> 00:24:38.249
The downside of that is there's not really
room to put a big list that needs a bunch

00:24:38.249 --> 00:24:39.249
of screen space.

00:24:39.249 --> 00:24:40.249
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Of course.

00:24:40.249 --> 00:24:43.259
&gt;&gt;Ryan: So, really it was just one of those
things we just kind of had to give up and

00:24:43.259 --> 00:24:47.220
what I like about potentially bringing a combined
list of recent searches to the dashboard is

00:24:47.220 --> 00:24:52.419
suddenly you haven't given up that recent
search list and I think that can make up for

00:24:52.419 --> 00:24:53.419
it.

00:24:53.419 --> 00:24:57.570
In general, flights is, flights and hotels
were both designed in two different eras so

00:24:57.570 --> 00:25:02.210
flights was originally designed back when
Gingerbread was the king and ICS didn't even

00:25:02.210 --> 00:25:06.500
exist and Honey Comb was just on tablets,
which I think it's always just on tablets,

00:25:06.500 --> 00:25:07.899
but just on early tablets.

00:25:07.899 --> 00:25:13.379
Then I did hotels before I had an ICS phone,
though I think it had been announced, so the

00:25:13.379 --> 00:25:16.919
